  "prompt": "What is the best way to simplify [math]\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}}[/math] where defined?",
  "response": "To simplify the expression \\(\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}}\\), we can start by eliminating the fractional terms in the numerator and denominator. This can be achieved by multiplying both the numerator and the denominator by \\(x\\) (assuming \\(x \\neq 0\\)), which is the common denominator.\n\nThe expression becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{x \\left(x - \\frac{1}{x}\\right)}{x \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{x}\\right)} = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1}\n\\]\n\nNow we have:\n\n- In the numerator: \\(x \\cdot x - x \\cdot \\frac{1}{x} = x^2 - 1\\)\n- In the denominator: \\(x \\cdot 1 + x \\cdot \\frac{1}{x} = x + 1\\)\n\nSo we can rewrite our expression as:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1}\n\\]\n\nNext, we notice that \\(x^2 - 1\\) is a difference of squares, which can be factored:\n\n\\[\nx^2 - 1 = (x - 1)(x + 1)\n\\]\n\nThis allows us to rewrite our expression further:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{(x - 1)(x + 1)}{x + 1}\n\\]\n\nProvided that \\(x + 1 \\neq 0\\) (i.e., \\(x \\neq -1\\)), we can cancel \\(x + 1\\) from the numerator and denominator:\n\n\\[\nx - 1\n\\]\n\nHence, the simplified form of the given expression \\(\\frac{x - \\frac{1}{x}}{1 + \\frac{1}{x}}\\) is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{x - 1}\n\\]\n\nThis simplification is valid for \\(x \\neq 0\\) and \\(x \\neq -1\\).",
